</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaelrei>Kaelrei</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 3:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hawaii.rr.com/pratts001/sig_cropped.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> A pure merit system makes your guild weak in the end.  You get bards/paladins/SKs/clerics passed over for plate in favor of warriors.  Rangers/bards/rogues get passed over for weapons.  Necros/mages get passed over for casting items.<br>
<br>
It doesn't work.  Sooner or later your non-trinity classes get disillusioned, tired of spending all their playtime equipping the warriors/chanters/clerics and begging for scraps.  And you end up with a guild that doesn't have any bards/pallies/druids/rangers/necros/SKs, etc.<br>
<br>
Random rolling obviously doesn't work.  I think almost everyone here agreed on that.<br>
<br>
DKP works.  Casual raiders will complain that core raiders get more gear than they need, but really there's no such thing. An upgrade is an upgrade, and the more time you put in, the more stuff you get.  It's not fair if someone raids 10 times and gets 2 items, and you raid 2 times and get 2 items.  <br>
<br>
Paying your DKP points balances out DKP perfectly.  If you only get 1/2 of a DKP point for killing the Vindicator, and the breastplate costs 25DKP to buy, your core raiders don't just mindlessly AYE for it, as Glatius is suggesting. It doesn't work that way. They save their DKP for the things they really want.<br>
<br>
For example, Joe has gone to 30 raids and saved up 28DKP.  Bob has gone to 10 raids and saved up 8DKP.  The vindicator dies and Joe and Bob want the breastplate.  The raid leader compares their points.  30&gt;8 so Joe get the breastplate.  However, it cost Joe 25 points, so now Joe has 5 DKP.  Then they go off and kill Zlandicar, and both say AYE on the cracked claw.  Let's say it costs 2 DKP.  Raid leader compares...  Joe has 6 (Zlandicar was worth 1) and Bob has 9.  9&gt;6 so Bob gets the claw and pays 2 DKP for it, leaving him with 7, which is STILL more than Joe has.<br>
<br>
I completely fail to see what's not fair about this.  There's no favoritism, there's no class-based elitism, no one is being taken advantage of. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 7:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Raid loot policies and guild progression</span><hr size=1> Our guild has a custom attendance-based points system with major addendum specific to main tanks.  It involves extra commitment and effort on the part of the tank but in return selected tanks get a limited ability to trump-card items(though they still spend points on them).<br>
<br>
So far that has worked out pretty well for us.  I think we had a couple 100hp items go to MTs as well as an Earring of Endless Speed.<br>
