</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 726<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 8:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I completely fail to see what's not fair about this. There's no favoritism, there's no class-based elitism, no one is being taken advantage of.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't think anyone said that DKP was unfair as far as a strict reward for service view is concerned.  But it can cause an uneven distribution of loot whereby the players who play the most get the majority of the upgrades.<br>
<br>
Let me see if I can put it in a way that makes sense.  If you have a total of 10 BP upgrades available to the guild in a 3 month period, all of which are within the same ball park of usefulness but perhaps some have a clicky effect that is desireable or resists or some other nice to have but not have to have characteristic.<br>
<br>
Now, a DKP system could very easily create a situation where those 10 BPs actually end up in the hands of 5 or 6 people, because they raid the most, they have a back log of raid points, and there are no penalties or disadvantages for them to take as many loots as they want as long as they have points.  So of those 5 or 6 people, they might see small advantages to this or that upgrade, loot one in one raid, loot another in the next raid and destroy the first.<br>
<br>
Rather than having 10 high caliber BPs spread around your guild members, you end up with say 6.  You've lost the advantage of 4 of those BPs, while still being perfectly fair.  If this concept doesn't bother you, then you'll see nothing wrong with DKP. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaelrei>Kaelrei</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 1:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hawaii.rr.com/pratts001/sig_cropped.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Glatius wrote:<br>
Rather than having 10 high caliber BPs spread around your guild members, you end up with say 6. You've lost the advantage of 4 of those BPs, while still being perfectly fair. If this concept doesn't bother you, then you'll see nothing wrong with DKP. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Your scenario leaves out the spending points part of DKP, though.  Yes, 5 or 6 could end up with all 10 BPs. But then those 5 or 6 took some very serious DKP point hits to their totals, leaving a window open for more casual players to get upgrades in the next couple weeks.<br>
<br>
Over time it works out.  The heavier raiders do end up with more, but the casual raiders get things too.  And if you want to look at a purely guild-based viewpoint, that's better for the guild too.  It's a waste to spend your guild's resources getting someone full PoP armor when that person shows up maybe 1 out of 5 raids.  Better to equip your main group of raiders first.  In this way, DKP also is great. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yrocmorf>Yroc Morf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 2:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.rogers.com/shadowedblade/yroc2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> I have always thought DKP comes at the expense of burn out on the part of the officers and leaders of a guild (or whom ever does all that damn paper work and book keeping).<br>
<br>
As for fairness, I truely think there is no equality in any of the afformentioned systems (nor any that someone can come up with).<br>
<br>
My guild has a loot policy that is &quot;open&quot;.  It allows the raid leader to choose a loot distribution system.  On rare occasions a member has put forth the idea of DKP and many members don't like it.  On some occasion /random has been used and there have been some complaints (allbeit very few major ones).  I myself and indifferent to what loot distribution system is used as long as it does not involve me becoming a bean counter in my leisure time.  The guild as a whole seems to favor the merit system.<br>
<br>
One thing you might find interesting.  <br>
<br>
Since we allow members to use... /random... weighted random... assigned loot... or even reserve loot for self, the next question comes to mind is.. What do they most often choose?<br>
<br>
Well so far.... Members most often org the raid, but ask that the normal &quot;loot council&quot; distribute loot (with them as an honorary member for that raid)...   <br>
<br>
I should note the loot council does on rare occasion decide /random is best for an item... but 99% of the time they just distribute it.  Loot council asks that those in need send a tell to one person.. who communicates with others who has asked for an item.  You would be absolutely amazed how many times no one... or only one person asks for an item.<br>
<br>
It is my opinion that this system works best for the guild as a whole and the only big issue with it is perceptions that those on the council might not be working &quot;for the guild as a whole&quot;.  You will note I say perception since I personally have complete confidence in their intention (and yes mistakes are made from time to time).<br>
<br>
The reason I know this is because I am on this council, but I should mention I find it too difficult to participate so I rarely cast a vote on anything (I'm sure the others in council think I'm lazy, but truth be known I really have a hard time choosing who should get 70% of the items that become available) for everyone is equally deserving in my mind.<br>
<br>
Anyhow ... I'm starting to babble, so I shall stop now...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=286390">Yroc Morf</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
