<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.neofrog.com/tips/cog.html">Make your own</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 730<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 2:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes, 5 or 6 could end up with all 10 BPs. But then those 5 or 6 took some very serious DKP point hits to their totals, leaving a window open for more casual players to get upgrades in the next couple weeks.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To a certain degree I imagine you're correct.  However my experience has been that the top raiders typically are able to regen their points at a fast enough rate that by the time the next piece of loot drops they want, bam, they have the points to get it, or at least make anyone else pay a very high price for it.  I've seen the same half dozen to a dozen players pick up the lion's share of the best loot because they were just able to do that much more raiding than the others.<br>
<br>
Granted, if the guild continues to raid the same mobs repeatedly over a period of time you'll reach a point where the top raiders have everything they would really want off the mobs anyway, which makes those drops more available.  But it does take a while.<br>
<br>
And then you have to ask if its better that your high performers be rewarded sooner or that your guild as a whole is rewarded sooner.  It's a pretty significant question.<br>
<br>
The DKP system works, don't get me wrong.  I just happen to feel that the rewards it gives can sometimes be overly focused into the hands of a small number of people.  While they may have 'earned' them, its not necessarily the best thing for the guild as whole.  It is however, just my opinion. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=diedraxev>DiedraXev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/22/03 3:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=32>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> Acctually Kaelrei, the post above which you said left out the spending part of DKP didn't necessarily.  There are two extremes that DKP systems go in.<br>
1) high cost, low point rewards<br>
2) low cost, high point rewards<br>
<br>
differance being that in 1 vindi BP may cost 100dkp and vindi raid gives 1dkp, where as in 2 vindi bp costs 1dkp and vindi raid is worth 100dkp.<br>
<br>
Obviously the numbers used are rediclously extreme but all DKP systems lie somewhere between the two extremes, extreme 1 leads to loot being spread out basically evenly and people skipping &quot;minor upgrades&quot;, where as extreme 2 tends to lead to the same few getting the best loot over and over again (the BP example that was used above to which you replied).  Both extremes obviously have problems, and in the ideal dkp system you have zero point growth/loss as a guild total (as in the number of dkp that come into the guild are equal to the number which leave the guild), but this is very hard to obtain.<br>
<br>
one way to do such would be dkp reward for raid = total loot value / number of people on raid.  but this leads to some raids with nice things not being worth it to anyone, DKP values with lots of decimal points, headache, et cetera.<br>
<br>
dkp in and of itself is still as worthless and unbalanced as any of the other systems, not until it is properly balanced cost/reward wise does it become &quot;more fair&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaelrei>Kaelrei</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/23/03 9:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.hawaii.rr.com/pratts001/sig_cropped.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> You're definitely right, and I was thinking that while reading Glatius' most recent reply.  It sounds like he's been in a DKP system where the raid gives too much DKP and the loot doesn't cost enough.<br>
<br>
The way my guild does it requires a lot of calculation and adjustment, but the result is that we haven't seen the kinds of problems Glatius is talking about.<br>
<br>
Let's say it takes your guild 30 people to kill the vindicator.  The way my guild would do it is to give each person 1 DKP for the encounter.  Then you look at the loot.  The earring and gloves really suck, so you assign maybe 1DKP cost to each of them.  But the breastplate and boots are very nice.  If it took 30 people to kill him, we'd likely make the breastplate cost 20-25DKP and the boots 5-10DKP.<br>
<br>
The idea is that the loot's total DKP should equal the amount of DKP you award total for the raid.  If you have more DKP going out than coming in, eventually people won't be able to buy anything anymore without going negative.  If you have more coming in than going out, then everyone amasses huge amounts of saved DKP, and the casual raiders can never get enough to ever get anything unless no one else wants it.  Both situations are eventually bad.<br>
<br>
A balance between the two works, but it doesn't work in a vacuum.  Let's say you get some upgrades or levels and now your guild can do Vindi with 18 people.  You need to adjust the loot DKP costs down to 18 to match, or your DKP economy goes screwy again. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 742<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/24/03 10:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> Just for the sake of discussion I'll go into a little more detail about the DKP system I was involved with and the inconsistencies it could create.  I imagine some or all of them could be countered in various ways if recognized.  These are of course solely my observations, other people would see it a different way, undoubtedly.<br>
<br>
The guild raided 5-7 days a week, depending on the available boss mobs. The guild was primarily an east coast US guild, so the majority of raiding took place during east coast prime time.  Frequently PST based players would be joining half way into the raids for that day.  Sometimes raids would continue past the time many EST players could participate, but this was somewhat less frequent.  As a result you had basically 4 tiers of raiders.  You had the east coast based hard core raiders.  You had the pacific coast based hard core raiders and the east coast moderate raiders (these are roughly one tier since they allow for roughly similar point potential).  You had the pacific coast moderate raiders and the east coast casual raiders (again one tier).  And finally you had the pacific coast casual raiders.<br>
<br>
Each boss mob would count for roughly 3 points.  There was some variation for the difficulty and length of time involved for each boss, but for the sake of ease of discussion we'll use 3 points as the average.  A typical week's raiding would give you perhaps the points potential of 40 points.  So here is how a typical points allocation might go.<br>
<br>
Hard core EST raider: 40 points<br>
Hard core PST and moderate EST raider: 30 points<br>
Moderate PST and casual EST raider: 20 points<br>
Casual PST raider: 10 points.    <br>
<br>
Now, as can be seen, using these admittedly somewhat hypothetical numbers as a guide, the Hard core EST raider could on the average spend 10 points a week more than the next tier and still stay competetive with that tier.  The Hard core PST raider could spend 10 points more than the tier below and still stay competetive with that tier.<br>
<br>
The system was a pure bid system, so you bid as much as you felt the item was worth to you.  An item could go for 1 point or for as many points as was available to the individual player.  Looting had no negative impact beyond lowering you available pool of points, so one person could gain as much loot on a particular run as they were able to win the bid on.<br>
<br>
As you can see the hard core EST raiders were quite capable of bidding on loot regularly and still keeping their points high enough to out bid anyone other than fellow hard core EST raiders.  I doubt that many of them were even aware of it, but it was true none the less.<br>
<br>
This meant that many times the best of the best loot went to one of the hard core EST raiders, time and time again.  And there were additional factors that skewed the bidding process.  Allow me to elaborate.<br>
<br>
For example, Monks.  There were only a small handful of perhaps 3 or 4 Monks in the guild.  Only 2 of them were hard core EST raiders.  Now there are a few extremely attractive Monk only items in the game.  When these items dropped, they usually went for a mere pittance, because the Monks had a gentleman's agreement between themselves that they wouldn't get into a bidding war.  This meant that they paid a token amount for Monk only items and had more points to spend on those items other classes shared that they might want.  <br>
<br>
Another example, Rogues.  A number of the Rogues decided they were going to horde their points and use them on the very best upgrades available, and not settle for anything less.  So they modestly geared themselves early in fairly common and inexpensive drops and then waited for the big stuff.  There were a couple of Rogues with close to 200 back logged points to be used at their discretion.  Because they could get by quite handily without the upgrades in between, they just didn't bother wasting points on them.<br>
<br>
Warriors however were a different story.  Warriors tended to bid on every drop that might possibly improve them in any significant way.  Basically because they needed as much of an advantage now rather than later as they could get.  So quite often the Warriors were one of the most points starved of the classes, particularly because what was good for a Warrior was typically also good for a Paladin or a Shadow Knight.  One of the problems would be situations like this though.  Warrior X, a hard core EST raider, would see item A drop that would give him a 25 HP improvement.  Warrior Y, a hard core PST raider, would see the same item and see that it would give him a 75 HP improvement.  Warrior X would win the bid, knowing that he would easily be able to recover the points in a week or two, and was still able to compete with the tier below him.  Since the item Warrior X was already using was invariably no drop it would be destroyed or banked.  Thereby you have one Warrior receiving a 25 HP improvement over another Warrior where it would have been a 75 HP improvement.<br>
<br>
Now was all this fair?  Certainly.  The system was set up in a certain way, everyone abided by the rules and had an equal opportunity to use the system to their advantage.  Would this necessarily be the best approach for the guild as a whole?  I believe that is open to some debate.<br>
  <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=khumak>Khumak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 218<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/24/03 1:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1771.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DKP</span><hr size=1> Well there's basically 3 different systems for distributing loot on raids.  All of them have their pros and cons.<br>
<br>
1.  Open lotto<br>
<br>
pros: requires no effort to implement<br>
cons: 100 percent reliant on the RNG.  <br>
opinion: Fine for pickup xp groups, retarded for raids<br>
<br>
2.  Merit based system<br>
<br>
pros: generally the people who show up for all the raids and play key roles (MT, puller, chain clerics, etc) get heavily geared up so you get the most bang for your buck from the perspective of guild strength<br>
cons: heavily susceptible to corruption and favoritism and prone to endless arguments<br>
opinion: great for guild only xp groups and very small tight knit raid guilds, destined for failure in most large raid guilds unless the leaders are extremely fair<br>
<br>
3.  Point system<br>
<br>
pros: when set up properly gives a good mix of upgrade oportunities for new members while still giving the hard core members priority based on higher attendance rather than favoritism (ie.  if you put in the time, you have earned whatever advantage you have in points)<br>
cons: if set up poorly it can result in anything from a free for all on loot to a lockout of all but the most hardcore players on most loot<br>
opinion: too complicated for xp groups or pickup raids, great for large raid guilds if enough care is taken in setting up points, tiers, etc. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=472195">Khumak</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Overlord of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.primordialfury.org">Primordial Fury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
